The right-wing populists in Austria are winning, 29% of the vote
A noticeable weakening of both parties in the previous grand coalition and a marked strengthening of the right-wing populist parties led to early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday, according to the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly heavy losses, with the position of its former chairman, Wilhelm Molterer, seriously threatened.
In contrast, the election leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthia's Landshauptmann Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but it loses 5.5 percent of the votes compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse was the performance of the ÖVP, which lost almost nine percent of the vote at 25.6 percent.
This is the worst result for the two major parties in the post-war history of Austria, and especially for the People's Party, which had demanded early elections, this is a truly disastrous result.
In July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the People's Party had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
But voters probably punished the party for failing the government.
The first reactions to the results were speculations about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could be the case at an extraordinary meeting of the party's board on Monday.
Such a development would probably pave the way for the most likely way out of the electoral debacle, i.e. a renewal of the grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
The Social Democrats, however, expressed their fear that the same situation could be repeated in 1999 when the People's Party reached agreements with the Populists (at that time the FPÖ was still united, but in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) on a joint government, which had even prompted sanctions from the European Union.
This is obviously the case with Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with any party and that he expects a return to Vienna in Austrian federal politics.
The Greens also entered the Parliament, but suffered minor losses and fell from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
No other party is likely to have won the four per cent threshold and therefore not entered parliament.
