Turkey expands its diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, the European powers were keen to penetrate deep into Turkey's hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosporus, perhaps only 20 paces inside Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed imperial endeavor.
Hydarpasha Station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the guides tell you.
The building sits at the end of the platforms with a tower at each corner of the front, making it look like some provincial German town hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building is falling apart.
But once you're inside the arched ticket counter, there's no doubt about the grandeur of the project, whose westernmost access was this.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Company.
Germany, being a latecomer in the imperialist game, had to implement its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by means of a train connection to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond to what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperialist plans were crippled during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from the surrounding region, created by the insurmountable borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
British forces were moving out of Egypt and pushing the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was also bad news for the Hyderabad Railway Station.
In 1917, a train of munitions blew up the elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly fallen into disrepair, largely forgotten by history.
Today, however, this railway line serves, at least symbolically, as a gateway to Anatolia and everything to the east of it, to highlight the expansion of Turkey's diplomatic horizon.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has introduced a radically new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from neighbouring regions, created by the borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
We are now in a state of rapprochement.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the key elements of this new foreign policy, I took the night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the leading ACP experts on foreign policy, the Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on the tracks that produced the old world pace in the famous documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is seen as the new city for the new secular state project of turning its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, which is known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity.
This has caused a lot of suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the main office of the AKP, a purpose-built, state-of-the-art stone and steel structure in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-finished shopping malls and pubs where middle-level managers in suits, both men and women, met to close the first trades of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exception", he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Nowadays, she has to look both east and west at the same time.
There's no one or the other.
She'd have to do both.
"But surely Turkey could be forced to make a choice at some point", I asked.
"Turkey", he said, "did not want to face this decision".
He then made a point which almost everyone I spoke to here has said almost routinely: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea region, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, Europe as a whole can, figuratively speaking, travel eastward on the same railways towards Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasa station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German gentlemen, Mr Knight and Mr Conu, who had watched this building being built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East could now be largely in the hands of Turkey.
And as I waited at the docks for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe" in those days.
At least at the time, there seemed little doubt as to which continent should claim this fascinating land.
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (calling on September 11th) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Choir.
As part of his musical program for the city, he founded his great youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was intended for youths under 21, but when the choir sang its last song in 1979, some of us were already in our late 20's - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological shape-shifter) stood for the choir's willingness and ability to take on any piece of music presented to it, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often astonishing, always exciting, and was due solely to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for music, which never waned over the years.
How often has death stopped us from "let the music speak for itself".
He used to say, "The composer knows what he wants".
It's all in the music.
So sing it!"
His style of conducting was absolutely clear and precise, never bossy but never exaggerated.
No matter how high the musical level, he always demanded a higher one.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, when he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic.
Over the last 40 years or so, I've written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts, and I can honestly say that I've never been disappointed by a single one - often I've been inspired by them.
Tod Handley was that rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He despised conductors who, he said, simply "walked around with one or two of the world's leading show horses".
So many of us will miss him.
