` Car bee', which avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan took inspiration from nature, more precisely from bees.
A Japanese company has developed a robot that mimics the flying behavior of swarms of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a bio-mimetic car robot drive or BR23C and represents the first step in accident prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Technical Development Center have developed this small robot in cooperation with the Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and R&D Brand Management, the BR23C is an extension of the four-layer Nissan safety shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid collisions.
During flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped flight space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But most importantly, the bee's multifaceted eyes, which can see in all directions at an angle of 300 degrees, allow it to fly undisturbed in its own personal airspace without interruption.
To recreate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed what is called a laser range finder (LRF).
It detects obstacles up to two metres away from the BR23C and within a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor which is immediately translated into a collision avoidance signal
` The moment an obstacle is detected, the little robot will mimic the flight of the bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at 90° or even higher to avoid the collision.
The main difference from any other system is that this evasive maneuver is absolutely instinctive.
If it were not, the robot might not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles,' explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the lead engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot move up or down, nor can it move across; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels, and not in the infinite directions and infinite ways that bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and braking functions, so that the little robot can avoid collisions.
` This device only needs a few seconds to process the information and act on it.
It does not require storing either the information or the intuitive logic of the maneuvers performed, so it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of storage space.
This sounds surprising, but it's not about the GBs, and it's not even about the MBs of storage.
This is the first step in the development of collision prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced in production cars within the next decade.
The robot operates on lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite to guide the driver to the destination while avoiding obstacles along the way.
