Morgan Stanley provides capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG) into its business, making it the first bank in Japan to issue $9 billion and thus acquire 21% of its capital, an innovation that is due to a sharp fall in its stock market price.
One week after a preliminary agreement was made public, the two banks announced that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common shares at a single price of $25.25, for a total of $3 billion.
The price assumed is below 19% of the share price at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible shares, which will provide it with a 10% return and can be resold at a price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley stated that the global deal will be done on the basis of a uniform average price of $29 which is 28% above the current market value.
Morgan Stanley shares, however, fell by 6.79% to $23.07 at 5pm GMT.
`This strategic link represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to holding bank status,' said John Mack, Managing Director of the American group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this status last week, which should allow it to expand its business into new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Your connection to MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to take a much more cautious stance than before.
The terms of the deal also show that the deal has changed over the past few days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
`A week ago', Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG, explained in Tokyo, `We thought that the holding would be entirely of ordinary shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation we wanted to reduce the risks and to protect ourselves.'
On the basis of a balanced average price, MUFG will pay 7% below the market value for its Morgan Stanley shares.
And the business will be able to recover with a reduction in earnings of about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into ordinary shares within one year, if the latter are exchanged within a given time limit at more than 50% above the sale value, i.e. at approximately 47 dollars.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds provided by MUFG will enable it to exploit investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its sales.
A spokesman for the group, however, declined to give any details on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following the investment by MUFG, Morgan Stanley should be able to achieve a solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the sector.
Morgan stated that it had reduced its balance sheet considerably since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been tough for the group, which has seen its stock market price fall by half as the price of insolvency insurance has skyrocketed.
This price decreased on Monday but remained at a high level, at around 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only other survivor of the big investment banks on Wall Street after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that it had withdrawn $15 billion, part of it from Berkshire Hathaway, the Warren Buffett group.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
The European Union is a democratic country.
This is the joint project of Hugo Chávez, a Venezuelan, Evo Morales, a Bolivian and Rafael Correa, an Ecuadorian.
It was the third who, following the example of his fellow-men and friends, voted for the draft of a new constitution on Sunday.
The Commission has fulfilled its mission, because according to the public results, which amount to 80% of the votes cast, 64% voted 'Yes' in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% voted 'no', 7% of the ballots were invalid and 0.7% were empty.
For the draft constitution to be adopted, one vote must be obtained for more than half of the votes cast.
On Sunday, two polls at the exit of polling stations and a count by an NGO had predicted a clear victory for the Yes, with 63% to 70% predicting it.
In the night from Sunday to Monday, by the way, Rafael Correa had demanded the victory of his draft constitution.
The Constitution has triumphed in a stunning way', he had assured in Guayaquil, the seat of government 280 kilometres south-west of Quito, and congratulated the Ecuadorians.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean counterpart, Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which was held in secret under the auspices of the Organization of American States (OAS), was on a 444-point text on securing the 'new socialism' for which the President is campaigning.
The draft constitution transfers state power to the economy by giving it the exclusive right to 'development planning' in a country which largely lives on oil extraction by foreign companies and on foreign exchange sent by emigrants.
The project, which is being promoted by Correa, elected in 2006, also grants the head of state more power, which will be able to serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the possibility to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also guarantees the principle of free health care and education, which the President has already begun to implement in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it also provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Ecuadorian base as a base for American anti-narcotics operations.
The 19 hostages freed in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched an attack on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight companions, who had been captured ten days earlier.
They're in Cairo.
The 11 European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions who had been held captive in the desert for 11 days were returned to the Egyptian capital this Monday afternoon, unharmed and unharmed.
The next morning they were liberated by an Egyptian command in Chad.
The hostages, apparently in good condition, arrived at the al-Maza military base near Cairo International Airport at about 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft.
They were taken directly, without being allowed to speak to the press, by helicopter to the hospital in Maadi, a foreign-born neighborhood of Cairo, for examination.
They are all in good health and no ransom has been paid to the kidnappers,' said Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna at the scene.
After being captured on September 19 while on an off-road safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat on the border between Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages were repeatedly moved from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The tourists are 11 - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four chauffeurs, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptus agency, the organiser of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, aboard two helicopters, launched the attack at night, just before dawn.
'Shots were fired on both sides and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled,' said the official, who wished to remain anonymous.
He explained that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces had been sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
The head of the Italian diplomatic corps, Franco Frattini, was reporting from Belgrade, where he is currently, on the role played by Italian secret agents and special forces.
'We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our intelligence and special forces men,' he said, without elaborating.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
The Sudanese army had claimed the previous evening to have stopped a patrol vehicle carrying the kidnappers, killing six of them, including the leader from Chad, and arresting two.
The army stated that they were linked to a rebel group from Darfur, the Libération du Soudan-Unité (SLA-U) movement, which was immediately denied.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture is making headlines and is a central theme of the current election campaign.
That's all the better.
But one area of our cultural life continues to be forgotten.
Who will stand up and denounce the pitiful sums given to the small museums, archives, archaeological digs or national historic sites that are starving to death?
What politician will dare to remind the Federal Government that it neglects its monuments and its culturally significant buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, there are no proper laws to effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government is providing 3.5 million euros exclusively for the restoration of the Château de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
Our American neighbors have a constitution that says that the protection of cultural heritage is part of the American culture, and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all members of Congress and all districts of government, by mutual consent.
In Quebec, the Association of Historical Societies of Quebec, at least 40,000 volunteers, gathered in 211 historical societies, are working hard to get deeply involved in history, to save the many private archives with a few pennies, and to preserve the archaeological remains.
They are also often the watchdogs of our cultural heritage, protesting with the power of despair when funders and policymakers unleash their bulldozers on our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When will there be a stage for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize parts of Fortis Bank
The Benelux countries are trying to help the Belgian-Dutch Fortis Bank, which has been in turmoil since the US financial crisis, by partially nationalising it. The three countries are providing a total of EUR 11.2 billion to the banking and insurance institution, which also has branches in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held a high-level meeting over the weekend, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commission's Competition Authority.
In the euro area, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial crisis that has been going on for a year, so decisions now being taken in relation to the bank could be precedent-setting.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states are buying their respective shares of the bank, which amount to about 49%.
The Bank is likely to sell part of its holdings, in particular the insurance business acquired by the Dutch ABN Amro last year.
Fortis shares started a steep decline last week, with serious crisis scenarios already emerging in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is far too large to fail.
The institute's stock fell 12% on Friday to a 14-year low.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
In view of the current share prices, the market value of the group is EUR 14 billion, which is unrealistic according to the management.
Management believes that the $700 billion American bailout and the resulting uncertainty in the markets are responsible for the downward trend in Fortis's stock.
On Monday, however, prices rose slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed the new CEO of the Bank.
The financial institution was also looking for a private buyer, but no interested party with a factual offer was found.
The Belgian government, however, tried to reassure investors that they should not be afraid of their money.
The customers have not panicked, the bank's branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary Fortis has independent branches, but it also calls leasing companies its own.
Fox in the henhouse
Because of a person's drug use, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are privacy policies that in any case link the use of the drug data to the consent of the data subject.
These should be in an independent hand, otherwise we'll leave the chickens to the fox", says Richard Dick, the developer of the prescription data tracking program.
Insurance companies set the costs and the amount of the damage depending on the health of the customer and if the risk is overestimated, the insurance is not taken out at all.
In the past, the customer was sent for a medical examination and the contract was concluded only in the knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a far cheaper method: using the customer's identification number, he obtained the data from the pharmacies for the last year and a half, that is, which drugs were purchased, and the program calculates from this the disease of the customer and his state of health.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering medication, it would suggest that his blood fat levels are untreatably high, which would automatically put him at a higher risk.
There are several versions of the programme in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so that insurance companies have to deal with more paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many medications can be taken for different purposes, such as for migraines and hot flashes, but also for depression.
The latter is a high risk factor from the insurers' point of view, whereas the previous ones are not.
For the collection and processing of data, companies have been formed which ask for the consent of the patient before they obtain the data.
In the meantime, they are required to do so by law, although omissions have not been punished.
Some companies even process lab results and combine them with data on drug use to provide an even more accurate picture of the health of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time it is becoming more difficult to control its use.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect extends only to healthcare and insurance providers.
The bill has already been introduced in Congress, which would allow the government to control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough, so he wants to develop his program further so that the data can only be shared with the consent of the person concerned.
The other question is, of course, that the person concerned can hardly refuse access to his data, since otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are left to the mercy of the fox.
