The European Union and India double trade
As the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, this was the main topic of the Ninth Summit, alongside other global issues.
The French-Indian summit is also taking place today, and the main topic of discussion is cooperation in the nuclear energy sector.
The European Union recognizes that India is an emerging democratic power which should be given more say and say in international affairs, but the Member States have so far been unable to agree on whether or not to support New Delhi's permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
This question was not even discussed at the ninth summit in Marseille yesterday.
The French President and current EU Council President Nicolas Sarkozy, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Chief Diplomat Javier Solana received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh.An agreement was reached to double trade to more than EUR 100 billion over the next five years.
Given that trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not even an ambitious target.
In this context, the 26 existing civil aviation agreements with India have also been legally merged into one agreement, thus also providing a boost to air transport in the future.
India intends to sign the Free Trade Agreement with the Union by 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim is to strike a balance in the currently unbalanced relationship between the EU and India: while the Union is India's number one partner, New Delhi is only ranked ninth among EU partners.
The summit was devoted to global concerns.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, and terrorism, which both sides strongly condemned, were among them.
The Doha Round should also be concluded, with both sides blaming each other for the failure.
The EU stressed that it was sticking to its energy and climate agenda, which is to reduce emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India agreed to this, as did the proposal to make some kind of global compromise at the upcoming climate summit, and to cut greenhouse gas emissions by 50 percent by 2050.
The European Union and the United States are also committed to the fight against food price increases, and they are therefore in favour of an international conference on the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister is visiting the French capital today, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, on the other hand, the expectation is that French firms will be awarded contracts worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of nuclear reactors in India.
According to agency reports, the agreement is to be concluded for 15 years.
