Billionaire Steve Fossett 's small plane , which disappeared a year ago , has been found .
The small plane belonging to Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The fragments were found on a high plateau at an altitude of 3,000 m in the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes region between the states of California and Nevada.
However, no human remains were found inside the plane.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson completely debunked the last of his doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been located, and a team has been dispatched to it, and we now have the certainty that it is the plane that Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared".
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found on or near the plane.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The US National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) reported that a team was sent out to identify the aircraft, the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on 3 September 2007 after Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada, for a three-hour flight, just hours after it was spotted.
Finally, yesterday, in California, near the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal effects were found by a couple near their home on Mammoth Lakes.
These are two IDs in the name of Fossett, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history through a long string of records.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he became the first human to orbit the globe in a hot air balloon, a two-week solo flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world in a single non-stop flight with an airplane.
Among his many records is a high-altitude flight of 15,445 m over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
